@dzhangalibaba Fixed in buildimage and also Jenkins config.

It is impossible to review such a large modification in one PR. It is better to split it into different sub features and submit many small PRs. I believe SONiC community won't accept such a big changes in one PR.

I am still reading this PR and design doc. I have one generic question about combing the config change and telemetry  together into the same gnmi agent. Could you please justify its motivation?

For me, I have two concerns:
1.)	The config flow is usually  time sensitive. Telemetry traffic load can be very high and may affect the config flow. 
2.)	The security requirement for telemetry and config are different. We don’t want to give telemetry application capability to change device.  Will you give different rights to different client based on their cert?
multiDB changes is merged in sonic-telemetry, suggest have a try if this PR needs adjustment when multiDB introduced.

the current makefile is already changed which is using "go mod" to manage local source codes and able to build with local changes. You may want to pull the latest sonic-telementy module and see. I suggest using "go modules" instead of the changes in current PR.

from the online discussion, looks after the changes telemetry depends on sonic-mgmt-framework, this not good. telemetry as a independent feature should NOT have any dependency on other dockers.

@dzhangalibaba  Could you please share more info about this dependency. It sounds not correct! - Hui Ma

My understanding is if sonic-mgmt is disabled , then sonic-telemetry will not work any more. Sonic-telemetry needs some lib from sonic-mgmt build.

@dzhangalibaba it isn't clear to me if go modules supports patching your dependencies before building them. We apply several patches to the dependencies we are using. Are you aware if this is supported?

> @dzhangalibaba it isn't clear to me if go modules supports patching your dependencies before building them. We apply several patches to the dependencies we are using. Are you aware if this is supported?

My understanding is patching whatever you want first and then "go module" will take all the local codes(original and patched) as source codes. I haven't tried this before, maybe my understanding is wrong.

@dzhangalibaba From my reading, there is a "replace" directive to point to a local copy, and there is a "go mod vendor" to allow for local vendoring, so I am experimenting with these. The other issue is that telemetry relies on sonic-mgmt-framework as a dependency which has also not converted to go modules.

> @dzhangalibaba From my reading, there is a "replace" directive to point to a local copy, and there is a "go mod vendor" to allow for local vendoring, so I am experimenting with these. The other issue is that telemetry relies on sonic-mgmt-framework as a dependency which has also not converted to go modules.

My understanding is  telemetry should NOT relies on other submodule like sonic-mgmt-framework at source codes level, they can share library , but when building one submodule, why it is  needed to use other submodule's source code?

@dzhangalibaba making the dependency as library and putting that as a docker layer will be coming later as that will take longer time to implement. With this PR we agreed to remove the dependency of compiling the mgmt-framework to compile telemetry(That we have already incorporated). Also converting the mgmt-framework to use go modules will also be incorporated in the subsequent PRs. With this PR we will try to have the Go module changes incorporated into the telemetry PR changes.
@dzhangalibaba Please do let us know your thoughts on the above plan.

> @dzhangalibaba Please do let us know your thoughts on the above plan.

Sounds good.  As I said before, two main stuff in this PR:
1 . if the "go module" is taken care in sonic-telemetry, that's good
2. try if any changes are need with the latest multi DB changes, most likely you don't need to change anything, just make sure telemetry works with the latest code base and pass UT.

other stuff like converting the mgmt-framework to use go modules and making the dependency as library could be done in following PR later.
@dzhangalibaba We will take care of the two things in this PR itself.

I have completed the conversion for our telemetry to use go modules. I also restored the location of all the files, so you can see only 19 files are reporting as changed now. I tested everything is building correctly with go modules. I will post tests results shortly.
